eading provider of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> independent </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">educational</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> tests and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> assessments</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, including stakeholder surveys.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">GL Assessment specialises in literacy, numeracy, reasoning, SEN and attitudinal assessments, and has relationships with over 85% of UK primary and secondary schools. Tests are nationally standardised, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">giving measures such as National Curriculum levels and standard age scores, and include parental reporting where appropriate. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Assessments include the Pupil Attitudes to Self and School (PASS) attitu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">dinal survey, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the Cognitive Abilities Test (CAT)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and Kirkl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and Rowell Surveys</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (provided by GL Assessment’s sister company GL Performance)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In-depth interpretation services help to identify appropriate intervention strategies. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 23pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We believe that the best means of improving the attainment of all pupils, including whi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">te working class children</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is through the use of consistent formative assessments and intervention programmes. This should include </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">active </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">parental engagement to ensure that parents are having a positive involvement in their children’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">education</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 23pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Formative</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> assessments allow schools to identify pupil difficulties </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">while attitudinal assessments can pinpoint </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the causes of any behavioural problems. Tackling these </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">together </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">will improve attainment and ultimately help address the underachievement of white working c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">lass children. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 23pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Response</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 23pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">GL </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Assessment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> works with schools across the UK, helping them to identify pupils who are underachieving and supporting the implementation of intervention programmes to improve pupil attainment. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 23pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Low attainment among white working class children, particularly boys, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">appears to be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">increasingly problematic</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Only recently the Centre for Social Justice published a report which showed that only “26 per cent of white British boys eligible for FSM achieved</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> five A* to C grades at GCSE including English and mathematics, compared to 36 per cent of all pupils on FSM, 63 per cent of all other pupils, and, for example, 40 per cent of black boys on FSM”.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 23pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We believe that the best way to tackle underachievement </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and to improve the attainment of all children, including white working class children, is through the use of consistent formative assessments. This allows schools to identify those pupils that are underachieving or having difficulties in certain areas, und</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">erstand the causes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of these problems and introduce targeted interventions to tackle them.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 23pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Steps for Schools to Take to Improve Educational Outcomes</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 23pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A formative assessment and intervention regime should be introduced from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">early years </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to ensure that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">any individual difficulties are identified and addressed before they become entrenched.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> progress check</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> provided for a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ll children at age 2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is an important policy that allows health visitors to identify any developmental problems that could cause childre</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n difficulties</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> at school. As part of the Healthy Child Programme, h</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ealth visitors across </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the UK</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> have successfully used </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">GL </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Assessment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Schedule of Growing Skills</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (SGS) to assess children’s developmental levels. SGS provides a reliable ‘snapshot’ of a child’s developmental level, including areas of strength and potential delay. It assesses development across nine key areas, including physical, cognitive, speech and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> language, and social interaction. SGS provides a standardised tool for developmental screening and encourages consistency in assessing the development of pre-school children from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">working class</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> families. The impact of a low income on child development can </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">be seen even at </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">this </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">early age </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">erefore it is vital that development is properly assessed and interventions are introduced early so that children are fully prepared to start full time education.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 23pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The use of SGS has proved particularly successful in Wa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">les as part of the Flying Start programme</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Flying Start was</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> introduced to help children from areas of deprivation to reach key developmental milestones.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Carmarthenshire </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">SGS </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">was used by</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> health visitors to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">identify developmental problems and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">assess the pr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ogress of children in the programme. At age 2 61% of children achieved scores in cognitive tests that showed they were at or above their chronological age. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This highlighted where children needed more support to improve their development, allowing for appro</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">priate interventions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to be made</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. When the children were reassessed with SGS at age three</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">84%</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> achieved cognitive scores at or above their chronological age</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> This was a significant improvement and shows the value of introducing proper formative assessment a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nd intervention regimes from an early age.</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 23pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As well as having a crucial role in early years, a consistent formative assessment and intervention programme should also be implemented in all schools</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. This is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a key means of improving educational outcomes for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">all children, but particularly children from working class families. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">For example in Rhondda Cynon Taf, an area of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">significant socio-economic disadvantage</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, formative assessments have been used successfully</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">as part of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">recently concluded</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> three year projec</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t, Building the Future Together</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. This project was introduced t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">o tackle the disengagement of 11-19 year olds across all 19 secondary schools </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in the area.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> A combination of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Cognitive Abilities Test</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CAT</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Pupil Attitudes to Self and School</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (PASS) attitu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">dinal survey</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> helped to pinpoint where interventions would have the most impact, reducing the number of NEETs and improving future employability. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 23pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is important that the assessments used as part of such a regime provide detailed, standar</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">dised reporting specifically on the results achieved by disadvantaged children. Along with more general reporting, this would allow a direct comparison to be made between these children and their more advantaged peers, both in their school and nationally.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 23pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">For example, one assessment that is widely used in UK schools, particularly at the transition between primary and secondary school, is the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Cognitive Abilities </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Test</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (CAT). CAT </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cannot be prepared for as it measures underlying reasoning abilities and therefo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">re provides schools with a comprehensive profile of a pupil’s developed abilities.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> It enables schools to identify pupils’ potential, set aspirational targets and drive school improvement.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 23pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CAT provides schools with a solid basis for introducing targeted </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">interventions to improve pupil attainment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, particularly in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> literacy and numeracy. Ideally it is used in conjunction with other formative assessments such as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Progress in Maths</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (PiM) and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Progress in English</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (PiE) which assess attainment as well as ability le</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">vels in maths and English. By comparing these results to CAT scores, teachers can see where pupils are not yet reaching their potential and implement improvement strategies. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 23pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">At the Knights Academy in Lewisham</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> CAT data has proven crucial to the school</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rapid improvements in pupil </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">attainment. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Academy is based in a very deprived area and a significant proportion of its pupils are on free school meals. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The school encourages aspiration in all pupils and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">o support this CAT is used to assess</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> all pupils in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Y</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ear 7</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. The data provided by CAT </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">has allowed the school to understand their pupils’ potentia</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">l, introduce interventions and targets </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and track progress by then r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">eassessing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">all </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">pupils</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in Year 9</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> This system of formative assessment and intervention has proved</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> successful; over six years the Academy increased outcomes by 55% and doubled the number of pupils continuing to further education.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 23pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As well as providing detailed reporting on individual pupils, which is key for the identification of those pupils in need o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">f targeted support, CAT also provides analysis </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the results of pupils by group, including by gender</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and ethnicity</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">those eligible for free school meals</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. As CAT is a nationally standardised </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">test, schools</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">can</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> compare the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">results </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">these </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">group</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> pupils </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">other pupils in their cohort</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, not only</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> within the school but also at a national level. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">omparisons by gender</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> or ethnicity</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> can help schools identify if there are any particular areas of difficulty among boys co</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">mpared to girls (or vice versa), or </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">white children compared to children of other ethnicities, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and introduce appropriate support to tackle these issues. Schools should be encouraged to collect this type of data by governing bodies and local authorities. This will help them to understand how w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">orking class pupils at the schools they are responsible for are achieving and identify what work needs to be undertaken to improve the outcomes of these pupils. Local authorities in particular should use this data to identify those schools that are able to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> produce good pupil outcomes and note examples of best practice to be shared with those schools that are less successful. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 25.08pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In order to properly monitor the success of schoo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ls in improving pupil outcomes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> schools </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">should implement progress tracking systems </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">alongside a consistent formative assessment regime. It is crucial that with any progress monitoring, and indeed with the use of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">formative assessments</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> as a whole</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, full training is provided for all teachers </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and school leaders </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">on the proper interpretation and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> use of data to inform </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">pupil </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">improvement.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Ultimately this will help improve the outcomes for children from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">working class</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> families by identifying any weaknesses early and monitoring their progress consistently. As the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">se children</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> approach statutory examinati</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ons schools will be able to identify early on if the required progress is being made and introduce further interventions if necessary.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 23pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Importance of Engagement</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">- </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Parents</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Research has shown that for children between the ages of seven to 16, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the involveme</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nt of parents</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in their schooling had a greater influence on attainment than family background, size of family and level of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">parental education</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Parental engagement with their child’s education can </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">have </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a real impact on attainment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and a parent’s attitude to school, often based on their own experiences of education, can also significantly affect their child’s attitude</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and subsequent achievement</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 23pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As such it is vital that schools work to build positive </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">relationships with parents and engage with them about their children’s education. For example, stakeholder perception surveys, like Kirkland Rowell Surveys, can identify any areas where parents are dissatisfied and those who may, as a result, not be provid</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ing appropriate support for their children, impacting on their attainment. By understanding parent perceptions schools can work to make improvements and also identify those pupils who may need additional support from the school to mitigate any lack of supp</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ort at home.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 23pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Similarly it is also important that schools are able to engage with parents regarding the results of any formative assessments that their child has taken. If parental support for any interventions is to be received it is important that they u</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nderstand why intervention is necessary. To support schools with this GL</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Assessment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> has developed parent</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">al</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> reporting for a number of the company’s assessments. This allows parents to understand the assessment process and for the schools to engage with them</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> as intervention programmes are developed and implemented. This type of reporting is a crucial aspect of the parental engagement needed to support improvements in working class children’s attainment and should be a feature of all formative assessment regim</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">es.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 23pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Importance of Engagement - Pupils</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 24.88pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As part of this process of engagement, it is important that schools also develop a full understanding of the attitudes of working class pupils towards education. Negative attitudes to school can lead to poor behavio</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ur and absences which ultimately have a detrimental effect on attainment. It is therefore important that schools assess pupil attitudes and work to address any problems. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 24.8pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">For example, the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Pupil Attitudes to Self and School</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (PASS) attitudinal survey is use</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">by over 2500 schools and over 100 local authorities across the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to address behavioural problems such as persistent absences. The survey is comprised of short psychometric statements that feed into nine attitudinal factors linked to key educational goal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s. These include how well children are responding to the curriculum, how prepared they are to learn and their attitude towards attendance. A low score in any factor can accurately pinpoint negative attitudes that may not otherwise be apparent. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 23pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Disengagem</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ent, poor attitudes to attendance and low self-confidence can manifest as poor behaviour and truancy and ultimately have serious detrimental impacts on pupil attainment. PASS can help to identify previously unknown areas where pupils may be disengaged or h</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">aving difficulties and help schools to introduce targeted interventions before these problems become entrenched. </span><a name="_GoBack"></a></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 24.8pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">PASS is especially helpful in terms of addressing absences as it </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">demonstrates a high correlation between students who have a low score in att</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">itude to attendance and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> their future</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> actual attendance.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Results indicated a very high (p. &lt;0.0001) correlation for the whole of the rating scale and the relationship between attitude to attendance and actual attendance was 0.91. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This means schools can</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> use </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">PASS to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> identify those pupils who are at risk of future poor attendance and address this before absences actually occur.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.32pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">For example, St Helens Council </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">has used PASS in local primary schools to identify pupils at risk of future absences at secondary school. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Council covers an area with severe deprivation, unemployment and high levels of teenage pregnancy. In 2007, National Strategies classed the author</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ity as a Persistent Absence (PA) local authority. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e Council was well aware </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that pupils who regularly miss classes are less likely to make good progress in school and are at greater risk of negative outcomes, such as youth crime and teen pregnancy. In or</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">der to tackle these problems the Council spoke to schools and identified the transition between primary and secondary school as a key time for the manifestation of poor </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">attendance </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">behaviours. The Council used PASS i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> local primary schools </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and it </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">revealed t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hat a significant number of girls had negative attitudes towards attendance but also had low self-regard and confidence in their learning. This allowed the Council to introduce intervention programmes to boost the girls’ self-regard and confidence, making </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">them feel happier at school and therefore less likely to truant. When PASS was used again after the intervention period their scores had significantly improved.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> The use of PASS also revealed that boys in particular found preparation for the SATs difficult.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> This knowledge allowed schools to build specific activities around SATs to help the children cope better.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 29.85pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">PASS can also be helpful in understanding the root causes of other poor behaviours, providing teachers with the information they need to improve them. For example, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Royal Manor Arts College in Dorset</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> found that two students who exhibited similar conduct had</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> very different causes. PASS revealed that one had no self-esteem but a good attitude to school and was well-motivated to learn. The other had high self-regard but a terrible attitude to school. This knowledge enabled teachers to tailor support appropriate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ly, building the confidence of the first student and ultimately improving their attainment while helping the other student to focus on their goals beyond school and put in the work needed to achieve them.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 24.59pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">For working class children who may not have</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> ne</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cessary support from home or who may not benefit from the same self-esteem and aspirations as their more well-off peers, this type of engagement is crucial for improving attainment. By tackling negative attitudes before they become entrenched schools can p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">revent them from manifesting into the truancy and poor behaviour that is ultimately damaging to attainment. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 23pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Government’s Role in Delivering Improved Educational O</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">utcomes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> for White Working Class Pupils</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 24.59pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The introduction of the Pupil Premium has been a va</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">luable way of providing targeted support to white working class pupils. We believe that this funding should be used by schools </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to support </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the implementation of formative assessment and intervention regimes. This will allow schools to identify </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">areas where t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hese pupils need extra support </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and ensure that their progress is consistently monitored so that by the time they reach statutory examinations they will be able succeed.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The use of Pupil Premium funding in this way also allows </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">schools to provide disadvantag</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ed pupils with additional </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">support in a way that does not identify them as being different to their </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">better off</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> peers. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Government should </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">therefore </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">be encouraging the use of formative assessments and in particular the use of the Pupil Premium to provide e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">xtra funding for such systems.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.12pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Conclusion</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 29.64pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">GL</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Assessment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> believes that a crucial means of addressing underachievement of white working class children is through the use of consistent formative assessment and intervention regimes. If this type of assessment is undertaken consistently from an early age, any diffi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">culties these children have can be identified and addressed before they </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">become entrenched. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This assessment should also include </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">assessment of pupil attitudes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, as well as a proactive system of parental engagement,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in order to address the root causes of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">disengagement or poor behaviour before they become entrenched. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Government should encourage schools to use formative assessments on all pupils </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">particularly for those eligible for the Pupil Premium. Such assessments provide schools with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">valuable </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">information they need to truly support their pupils and ultimately improve attainment.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> The Centre for Social Justice, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Requires Improvement: The Causes of Educational </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Failure</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> (September 2013), p.14.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Further information on the use of SGS in Wales, as well as the other examples of formative assessment use noted in this response, is available on request.</span></p></body></html>